Introduction¶

Using the OSEMN framework the project will go through the Data Science phases to get, clean, explore, model and interpret this dataset using the multivariate linear regression to predict the sale price of houses as accurately as possible.

Data Science Workflow¶

Understanding the typical work flow on how the data science process works is a crucial step towards business understanding and problem solving. Using the OSEMN Framework the student will go through the different steps of the framework in an iterative and non-linear process. The table of contents section just serves to organize the information in this project and the iterative process will be evident as the student reflect back the new information e.g. discovered from the exploration back to processing the data to gain the insight necessary to interpret the results of the model and communicate results to stakeholders.

  • O. Obtain the data
  • S. Scrubbing/ cleaning the Data
  • E. Exploring/ Visualizing the Data
  • M. Modeling the data
  • N. iNterpret the Data

Before we begin the OSEMN Pipeline the most crucial step is to understand the problem we are trying to solve. In this Module 1 Project, the student will be working with the home sales data from King County, WA. The primary objective is to predict home sales price by building a multivariate linear regression model that will make accurate quantitative predictions of data.

Multivariate linear regression model is used when we want to predict the value of a variable based on the value of two or more other variables. The variable we want to predict is called the dependent variable (or sometimes, the outcome, target or criterion variable). In this project, we would like to determine which features best predict the price of a home.

In this project we would like to find the answers to the following questions:

  • Which features have the biggest impact on home sale prices?
  • What is the Median Home Sale Price by Zip Code?
  • Where are the Top 20 Most Expensive Homes Sold located?
  • Do more bedrooms add value?
  • Do more bathrooms add value?
  • How does the condition affect the price of a home?
  • How does the grade (quality of construction and design) affect home pricing?
  • Which number of floors add the most value to the sale of a home?
  • What is the home construction history like at King County
  • What is the best month and day to sell a home?
  • What is the distribution of homes sold with views, waterfronts, or have undergone renovation?
  • Which features add the most value to home sales?

1e. Review of Data Types¶

The total number of observations(rows) = 21597

Here are a few other observations that we need to take into consideration in the next phase of scrubbing the data.

  • There are also missing data points in the view column (nan) in addition to the waterfront and yr_renovated columns.

  • Two non-numeric (object) variables were found. These will need to be converted to numeric.

    • date (object) - Date house was sold
    • sqft_basement (object) - square footage of the basement

  • There are several variables with numeric datatypes that should be converted as categorical variables.
    Column descriptions reference from Kaggle

    • floors (float) - Total floors (levels) in house
    • waterfront (float) - House which has a view to a waterfront
    • view (float) - Has been viewed? An index from 0 to 4 of how good the view of the property was
    • condition (int) - How good the condition is ( Overall )? An index from 1 to 5 on the condition of the home
    • zipcode (int) - zipcode area the house is located
    • grade (int) - overall grade given to the housing unit, based on King County grading system? An index from 1 to 13
      • 1-4 falls short of building construction and design
      • 5-6 unsatisfactory building construction and design
      • 7-8 has an average level of construction and design
      • 9-10 has above average of building construction and design
      • 11-13 have a high quality level of construction and design Value Definition 0 Unknown 1 Cabin 2 Substandard 3 Poor 4 Low 5 Fair 6 Low Average 7 Average 8 Good 9 Better 10 Very Good 11 Excellent 12 Luxury 13 Mansion 20 Exceptional Properties
  • There are two datepart numeric variables that should be converted as categorical variables.
    • yr_built (int) - The year the house was initially built
    • yr_renovated(float) - The year when house was renovated
  • The following variables are continuous variables.
    • price (float64) - Price of each home sold - the prediction target
    • bedrooms (int64) - Number of Bedrooms
    • bathrooms (float64) - Number of bathrooms, where .5 accounts for a room with a toilet but no shower
    • sqft_living (int64)- square footage of the home
    • sqft_lot (int64) - square footage of the lot/land space
    • sqft_above (int64) - square footage of house apart from basement
    • sqft_living15 (int64) - The square footage of interior housing living space for the nearest 15 neighbors
    • sqft_lot15 (int64) - The square footage of the land lots of the nearest 15 neighbors
    • lat (float64) - Latitude coordinate
    • long (float64) - Longitude coordinate

  • We know that view has 5 total unique values excluding NaN = [0.0, 3.0, 4.0, 2.0, 1.0].

2c. Fill in the missing values¶

In [69]:
# Since most waterfront is zero, fill in the waterfront missing values with 0, since houses are either with waterfront (1)or without (0).
df.loc[df.waterfront.isna(), 'waterfront'] = 0
df.waterfront = df.waterfront.astype('int')

# We have 5 unique values for view and we would like to use the median, for filing in the missing values. 
#In this case, the median is 0, which is also the mode for this column
df['view'].fillna(df['view'].median(), inplace=True )
df.view = df.view.astype('int')

# We will replace the NaN with 'missing' and the 0 value in the yr_renovated features
df.loc[df.yr_renovated.isna(), 'yr_renovated'] = 0

# Let's confirm that the missing values were filled in (verify increase in 0.0 totals)
display(df['view'].value_counts(), df['waterfront'].value_counts(), df['yr_renovated'].value_counts().nlargest(5))

What's the best time to sell a house? The best time to sell a home varies from market to market, some regions are counterintuitive to the national trend. For King County, home sales peaked during the spring (highest in May) and warmer months and declined during the fall and winter. Home Sales are highest on Wednesdays and generally on weekdays, but very low on the weekend. Here are some of the pros of selling during the spring and summer months:

  • more funds are available for repairs and renovations with tax refund money available around this time
  • more home buyers go out searching for homes with the warmer weather plus the curb appeal that spring and summer months offer when the trees, flowers and grass bloom
  • warmer weather is the best time to move with more daylight hours, as well as allowing kids to finish the school year as buyers close on a home/sellers have more time for showings
  • sense of urgency for buyers to get their school-aged kids settled What is the single best day where the highest number of homes were sold at King County?

#Let's check % of outliers https://www.kaggle.com/prasadperera/the-boston-housing-dataset
ncategoricals = dfc.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])
for k, v in ncategoricals.items():
        q1 = v.quantile(0.25)
        q3 = v.quantile(0.75)
        irq = q3 - q1
        v_col = v[(v <= q1 - 1.5 * irq) | (v >= q3 + 1.5 * irq)]
        perc = np.shape(v_col)[0] * 100.0 / np.shape(df)[0]
        print("Column %s outliers = %.2f%%" % (k, perc))

We will use the interquartile range (IQR), also called the midspread or middle 50% (H-spread), to measure the statistical dispersion by finding the difference between 75th and 25th percentiles, or between upper and lower quartiles, IQR = Q3 − Q1.

3c. Linearity check¶

Linearity assumptions requires that there should be a linear relationship between the target/criterion variable (Y) and predictor (X). Linear means that the change in Y by 1-unit change in X, is constant.

If we try to fit a linear model to a non-linear data set, Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) would fail to capture the trend mathematically. This will result in an inaccurate relationship and wrong predictions on an unseen data set.

The linearity assumption can best be tested with scatter plots. Outliers are revealed in a scatter plot and need to be dealt with as it will introduce bias that will prevent the model from providing accurate estimates on the relationships between variables.

In the above example, we can see that an outlier prohibit the model to estimate the true relationship between variables by introducing bias.

It is important that we have a normal distribution of the dataset and then we would want to do this transformation to get that normal distribution so it does not violate the normality assumption and allows one to use parametric statistics which follow the assumption the the data has a normal distribution and provide stronger ways to test for the hypothesis. https://help.gooddata.com/display/doc/Normality+Testing+-+Skewness+and+Kurtosis
    -If skewness is less than -1 or greater than 1, the distribution is highly skewed.
    -If skewness is between -1 and -0.5 or between 0.5 and 1, the distribution is moderately skewed.
    -If skewness is between -0.5 and 0.5, the distribution is approximately symmetric.

    Kurtosis is the 4th moment in statistics. It tells you the height and sharpness of the central peak, relative to that of a standard bell curve.

    • A positive value tells you that you have heavy-tails (i.e. a lot of data in your tails).
    • A negative value means that you have light-tails (i.e. little data in your tails).
    • This heaviness or lightness in the tails usually means that your data looks flatter (or less flat) compared to the normal distribution. The standard normal distribution has a kurtosis of 3, so if your values are close to that then your graph’s tails are nearly normal. These distributions are called mesokurtic.

Why transform? to reduce skewness, to have equal spreads, to prove linear relationships and additive relationships

3e. Multicollinearity check¶

In feature selection for a regression model, it is important to check for multicollinearity.
Multicollinearity means that some of the independent variables (regressors) are highly correlated with each other. If the regressors are highly correlated, it will be difficult to find the correct predictors and their precise effect on the target and may reduce the accuracy of the regression estimates.

Pearson's Correlation Coefficient or linear correlation coefficient measures the strength and the direction of linear relationship between two variables. Correlation is a technique for investigating the relationship between two quantitative, continuous variables, for example, price and sqft_living. Pearson's correlation coefficient (r) is a measure of the strength of the association between the two variables.
Pearson's r is sensitive to outliers, which can have a very large effect on the line of best fit and
the Pearson correlation coefficient, leading to very difficult conclusions regarding your data. Therefore, it is best if there are no outliers or they are kept to a minimum.
Assumption #1: Your two variables should be measured at the continuous level.
Assumption #2: There needs to be a linear relationship between your two variables.
Assumption #3: There should be no significant outliers.
Assumption #4: The variables should be approximately normally distributed.

Multicollinearity occurs when independent variables in a regression model are correlated, i.e. indicates that changes in one predictor are associated with changes in another one as well. This correlation
is a problem because the idea behind regression is that you can change one variable and keep the others constant. If the degree of correlation between variables is high enough, it can cause problems when you fit the model and interpret the results.
Generally, a correlation with an absolute value around 0.7-0.8 or higher is considered a high correlation.
We used 0.70 as a cut-off, how many high correlations do we have?

From the correlation plot, we can see the features listed below are highly correlated with each other.
-sqft_above
-sqft_living
-sqft_lot
-sqft_lot15

However, the highest correlation exists between sqft_lot and sqft_lot15 at 0.87 followed by sqft_above and sqft_living.
We will go ahead and remove sqft_above and sqft_lot15.

4b. Feature Scaling & Normalization¶

In Section 3d Normality check we have performed a visual check and can tell that the shape of our variable's data distribution have different levels of skewness issues and does not follow a normal distribution. The assumption for multivariate normality is essential if we want to do statistical hypothesis testing to allow us to generate reliable confidence intervals and prediction intervals. We need to transform our data to make it Gaussian-like and perform feature scaling to manage the difference in magnitude.
Feature scaling is a method used to standardize the range of independent variables/feature. It is used to scale the data in a specific range like -1 to +1 or -5 to +5 depending on the algorithm.If the data is not scaled or not normalized then we risk not getting the desired result and the result will be misleading. In addition if the data lies between the different mean values, it will result in two different standard deviations and variance so in order to achieve the expected output we need to transform the data in a similar range.

for x, val in enumerate(columns):
    print ("price~" + val)
    print ("------------------------------")

    f = 'price~' + val
    model = smf.ols(formula=f, data=df).fit()
    X_new = pd.DataFrame({val: [df[val].min(), df[val].max()]});
    preds = model.predict(X_new)
    results.append([val, model.rsquared, model.params[0], model.params[1], model.pvalues[1]])

    print(results[x + 1])
    print('\n')

#Let's create a for loop using RFE where we look at the 217 best features to be selected according to the feature ranking algorithm
y = df_final[['price']]
X = df_final.drop(['price'], axis = 1)

linreg = LinearRegression()

R2_list = [ ]
adj_R2_list= [ ]

for n in list(range(5,218,10)):
    selector = RFE (linreg,n_features_to_select = n)
    selector = selector.fit(X,y)
    selected_columns = X.columns[selector.support_]

    linreg.fit(X[selected_columns],y)

    yhat = linreg.predict(X[selected_columns])
    SSR = np.sum ((y-yhat)**2)
    SST = np.sum ((y-np.mean(y))**2)
    R2 = 1 - (SSR/SST)
    adj_R2 = 1 - (1-R2)*(len(y)-1)/(len(y)-X.shape[1]-1)

    R2_list.append(R2)
    adj_R2_list.append(adj_R2)

The Test MSEs have no significant difference with Train MSEs when we add variables. A bigger model will improve our performance, and the test and train performance have no divergence. Now, let's perform cross-validation on our model with all these predictors.

What we see is that both MSE started with almost the same score and keeps improving when we add variables. The test and train performance don't really diverge. Now, let's perform cross-validation on our model with 150 predictors. Our test error is the same as our train error, this could indicate that our model generalize well to future cases.

Let's test overfitting and underfitting by changing the size of our train test split. By default, scikit learn's built in method allocates 25% of the data to the test set and 75% to the training set. Fitting a model on only 10% of the data is apt to lead to underfitting, while training a model on 99% of the data is apt to lead to overfitting.

It helps to get a small mean absolute error (MAE) to help our model predict the output as MAE tells the average of the our variables residuals. The mean square error (MSE) is just like the MAE, but squares the difference before summing them all instead of using the absolute value. MSE will be bigger than our MAE and are influenced more by outliers in our data.

y_hat_test = linreg.predict(X_test)

#Look at residuals and MSE
#MSE works by taking the difference between each of the estimated and the real value, squaring them 
#and dividing their sum by the number of samples.
train_residuals = y_hat_train - y_train

mse_test =np.sum((y_test-y_hat_test)**2)/len(y_test)

5. iNterpreting the Data¶

MSE is the loss function, which in this case is low and gives intuition of the best fit estimate.
The lesser the MSE the smaller is the error and we can say that we have a good estimator because it implies agreement between the prediction and the reality.
Our estimator performed well in guessing the real values of the prices.
There does not seem to be a big difference between the train and test MSE. MSE’s value is in helping us to select one prediction model over another.

In this regression project, we try to measure the model parameters (coefficients ) so our null and alternative hypotheses can be accepted or rejected.

NULL HYPOTHESIS (Ho): There is no relationship between Home Sale price and location(zip), sqft living, waterfront, views, condition, etc..

ALTERNATIVE HYPOTHESIS (Ha): There is "some" relation between Home Sale Price and and location(zip), sqft living, waterfront, views, condition, etc.

Rejecting the null hypothesis would help us associate some significance with our results As per out model results, we reject the null (and thus believe the alternative) if the 95% confidence interval does not include zero for co-efficient. The p-value represents the probability that the coefficient is actually zero.

A low R-squared value means that the predictors in oour model do not describe the variation in our dependent variable. This project demonstrated that there are strong relationships between locations (zip/waterfront) and sq ft living area.

In the preliminary model fit the R-squared:0.87 and Adj. R-squared:0.86 are pretty good. The p values for the continuous variables, sqft_living, sqft_lot variable look good

87% variations in dependent variable Home Sale price is explained by the independent variable present in our model. 87% of variance in the home sale price can be explained by the independent variables on our model. The Intercept: A "unit" increase in sqft living is associated with a 0.3416 "unit" increase in Home Value. With alpha set to 0.05, we can claim to have 95% confidence on the outcome. **

R-squared or coefficient of determination is a statistical measure that is used to assess the goodness of fit of a regression model.

R-squared uses a baseline model which is the worst model because it does not make use of any independent variables to predict the value of dependent variable Y, but rather it uses the mean of the observed responses of dependent variable Y and always predicts this mean as the value of Y. We looked at the adjusted R squared to keep our model in check as this modified R squared will increase only if the new terms improves our model. In this case, the p-value for sqft living is less than 0.05, and so we believe that there is a strong relationship between sqft living and and Home Sale price.

We haven't learn about interpreting AIC or BIC in Module 1 but this model has negative values on the AIC & BIC. According to this forum (https://www.reddit.com/r/AskStatistics/comments/5ydt2c/if_my_aic_and_bic_are_negative_does_that_mean/) Negative AIC indicates less information loss than a positive AIC and therefore a better model from the set of plausible models being considered( the smallest AIC value the least information loss relative to the true model).
